{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500034"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:07:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:07:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1603"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1603"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.08,0.02,0.08,0.78]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1603"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53635"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1603"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1603"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39095"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"344"},{"type":"tags","id":"2149"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6114"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13981"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53635"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man five days post-total gastrectomy for gastric carcinoma is reviewed on the wards by the duty intern for. excessive coughing. He has a medical history of obesity and a 40 pack-year smoking history. He works as a truck driver. The initial operation was uneventful, although there were some technical difficulties due to the patient\u0027s body habitus. Postoperatively, he received aggressive chest physiotherapy. He reports  that he has not opened his bowels or passed flatus. He has been unable to mobilise or sit out of bed for prolonged periods. After a bout of coughing, the following appearance of his wound is noticed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Saline-soaked dressings","Negative-pressure wound therapy","Wound debridement","Abdominal binder","Return to the operating room"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has suffered a deep wound dehiscence with evisceration, which is a surgical emergency requiring immediate intervention. The most appropriate definitive management is an urgent \u003Cstrong\u003Ereturn to the operating room\u003C/strong\u003E for exploration, washout, and closure of the wound. Prior to surgery, the patient should be resuscitated if in shock and given broad-spectrum antibiotics. It is crucial not to attempt reduction of the eviscerated bowel at the bedside.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESaline-soaked dressings\u003C/strong\u003E could be applied as an immediate temporary measure to protect the eviscerated bowel while arranging for urgent surgery, but this is not a definitive management plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENegative-pressure wound therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for managing evisceration. It is typically used for complex or chronic wounds to promote healing, but it is contraindicated in the presence of exposed organs or blood vessels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWound debridement\u003C/strong\u003E might be warranted if there were signs of infection around the wound, and this would be performed in the operating room. However, in this case, the primary issue is the evisceration, which requires immediate surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal binders\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to increase patient comfort and support wound healing after abdominal surgery, particularly in patients with risk factors for poor healing. However, they are not appropriate for managing acute evisceration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights several risk factors for wound dehiscence, including obesity, smoking history, and increased intra-abdominal pressure from coughing and possible ileus. Proper management involves addressing the immediate surgical emergency and subsequently managing these risk factors to prevent recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Deep wound dehiscence with evisceration is a surgical emergency requiring immediate return to the operating room.","Risk factors for wound dehiscence include obesity, smoking, malnutrition, and increased intra-abdominal pressure (e.g., from coughing or ileus)."],"references":["Rosen RD, Manna B. Wound Dehiscence. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2021 May 9].  Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551712/","Saeed S, Rage KA, Memon AS, Kazi S, Samo KA, Shahid S, Ali A. Use of abdominal binders after a major abdominal surgery: A randomized controlled trial. Cureus. 2019 Oct 3;11(10). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31754567/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39095"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1603"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15563"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15563"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ad1c4d84-7b93-4963-81e5-0ca15912a7ad.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ad1c4d84-7b93-4963-81e5-0ca15912a7ad.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":450,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39095"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-2